es.htm |title=Special Recognition License Plates |author= |year=2011 |website=California Department of Motor Vehicles |publisher=State of California |accessdate=30 January 2013 }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.mdva.state.mn.us/extras/VeteranMilitaryPlates.htm |title=Minnesota Veteran, Military and related license plates |author= |year=2010 |website=Minnesota Department of Veterans Affairs |publisher=State of Minnesota |accessdate=30 January 2013 }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.oregon.gov/odot/dmv/pages/vehicle/platevet.aspx |title=Veteran & Military Service-related License Plates |website=Oregon DMV |publisher=State of Oregon |accessdate=30 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130211040513/http://www.oregon.gov/ODOT/DMV/pages/vehicle/platevet.aspx |archivedate=11 February 2013 }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.ksrevenue.org/dmv-medalofhonor.html |title=Kansas Medal of Honor Plate |year=2012 |website=Kansas Department of Revenue |publisher=State of Kansas |accessdate=30 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025164343/http://ksrevenue.org/dmv-medalofhonor.html |archivedate=25 October 2012 }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.transportation.wv.gov/dmv/vehicles/pages/personalizedplates.aspx |title=Special License Plates |year=2013 |website=West Virginia Department of Transportation |publisher=State of West Virginia |accessdate=30 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130201101205/http://www.transportation.wv.gov/dmv/Vehicles/Pages/PersonalizedPlates.aspx |archivedate=1 February 2013 }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.dmvnv.com/platesveterans.htm |title=Veterans License Plates |author= |year=2013 |website=Nevada Department of Motor Vehicles |publisher=State of Nevada |accessdate=30 January 2013 }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.colorado.gov/cs/Satellite/Revenue-MV/RMV/1201542141638 |title=Military Plates |author= |year=2013 |website=Department of Revenue |publisher=State of California |accessdate=30 January 2013 }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.state.sd.us/drr2/motorvehicle/licenseplates/medal_of_honor.htm |title=Congressional Medal of Honor License Plates |author= |website=South Dakota Department of Revenue |publisher=State of South Dakota |accessdate=30 January 2013 }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.dol.wa.gov/vehicleregistration/spmoh.html |title=Medal of Honor plates |author= |year=2013 |website=Washington State Department of Licensing |publisher=State of Washington |accessdate=30 January 2013 }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.lawserver.com/law/state/idaho/id-code/idaho_code_49-415a |title=Idaho Code 49-415A \u2013 Congressional Medal of Honor License Plates |author= |year=2013 |website=Vehicle Registration |publisher=LawServer Online, Inc. |accessdate=30 January 2013 }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.ok.gov/odva/Oklahoma_Veterans_Benefits/License_Plates/index.html |title=State Benefits |date=7 November 2012 |website=Oklahoma Department of Veterans |publisher=State of Oklahoma |accessdate=30 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201222906/http://www.ok.gov/odva/Oklahoma_Veterans_Benefits/License_Plates/index.html |archivedate=1 February 2012 }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.mvd.newmexico.gov/Vehicles/Pages/License-Plates-Details.aspx |title=License Plates Details |author= |year=2011 |website=New Mexico Motor Vehicle Department |publisher=State of New Mexico |accessdate=30 January 2013 }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.azdot.gov/mvd/vehicle/mvdplate.asp#MedalofHonor |title=Plates and Placards |author= |website=Arizona Department of Transportation |publisher=State of Arizona |accessdate=30 January 2013 }}</ref> The states that do not offer Medal of Honor specific license plate offer special license plates for veterans for which recipients may be eligible.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://myarmybenefits.us.army.mil/Home/Benefit_Library/State__Territory_Benefits/_New_Hampshire.html |title=State / Territory Benefits \u2013 New Hampshire |date=25 July 2012 |website=My Army Benefits |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=30 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130202005948/http://myarmybenefits.us.army.mil/Home/Benefit_Library/State__Territory_Benefits/_New_Hampshire.html |archivedate=2 February 2013 }}<br />{{cite web|url=http://myarmybenefits.us.army.mil/Home/Benefit_Library/State__Territory_Benefits/Rhode_Island.html |title=State / Territory Benefits \u2013 Rhode Island |author= |date=7 March 2012 |website=My Army Benefits |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=30 January 2013 }}<br />{{cite web|url=http://myarmybenefits.us.army.mil/Home/Benefit_Library/State__Territory_Benefits/Vermont.html |title=State / Territory Benefits \u2013 Vermont |author= |date=21 July 2011 |website=My Army Benefits |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=30 January 2013 }}<br />{{cite web|url=http://myarmybenefits.us.army.mil/Home/Benefit_Library/State__Territory_Benefits/Nebraska.html |title=State / Territory Benefits \u2013 Nebraska |author= |date=11 November 2010 |website=My Army Benefits |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=30 January 2013 }}<br />{{cite web|url=http://myarmybenefits.us.army.mil/Home/Benefit_Library/State__Territory_Benefits/North_Dakota.html |title=State / Territory Benefits \u2013 North Dakota |author= |date=23 September 2010 |website=My Army Benefits |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=30 January 2013 }}<br />{{cite web|url=http://myarmybenefits.us.army.mil/Home/Benefit_Library/State__Territory_Benefits/Montana.html |title=State / Territory Benefits \u2013 Montana |author= |date=5 October 2012 |website=My Army Benefits |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=30 January 2013 }}<br />{{cite web|url=http://myarmybenefits.us.army.mil/Home/Benefit_Library/State__Territory_Benefits/Wyoming.html |title=State / Territory Benefits \u2013 Wyoming |author= |date=30 December 2011 |website=My Army Benefits |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=28 January 2013 }}<br />{{cite web|url=http://myarmybenefits.us.army.mil/Home/Benefit_Library/State__Territory_Benefits/Utah.html |title=State / Territory Benefits \u2013 Utah |author= |date=28 June 2012 |website=My Army Benefits |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=30 January 2013 }}<br />{{cite web|url=http://myarmybenefits.us.army.mil/Home/Benefit_Library/State__Territory_Benefits/Alaska_.html |title=State / Territory Benefits \u2013 Alaska |author= |date=29 October 2012 |website=My Army Benefits |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=30 January 2013 }}<br />{{cite web|url=http://myarmybenefits.us.army.mil/Home/Benefit_Library/State__Territory_Benefits/Hawaii.html |title=State / Territory Benefits \u2013 Hawaii |author= |date=6 December 2012 |website=My Army Benefits |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=30 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Saluting===\n[[File:Defense.gov photo essay 110713-F-RG147-129.jpg|thumb|[[Admiral (United States)|Admiral]] [[Eric T. Olson]] salutes [[Sergeant First Class#United States Army|Sergeant First Class]] [[Leroy Petry]] at a ceremony at [[The Pentagon]].]]\n* Although not required by law or military regulation,<ref>United States Army. ''[http://www.smdc.army.mil/2008/CSM/docs/FM7_21_13.pdf The Soldier's Guide''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120903224919/http://www.smdc.army.mil/2008/CSM/docs/FM7_21_13.pdf |date=2012-09-03 }}. 2003. Chapter 4.</ref> members of the [[Uniformed services of the United States|uniformed services]] are encouraged to render salutes to recipients of the Medal of Honor as a matter of respect and courtesy regardless of rank or status, whether or not they are in uniform.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uscg.mil/auxiliary/cginfo/uniforms/custom.asp |title=USCG CG-5421 Web Site \u2013 Customs & Courtesy |publisher=Uscg.mil |date=February 18, 2011 |accessdate=January 3, 2012}}</ref> This is one of the few instances where a living member of the military will receive salutes from members of a higher rank.\n\n==Legal protection==\n{{Update|date=December 2016}}\n*1904: The Department of the Army redesigned its Medal of Honor, largely a reaction to the copying of the Medal of Honor by various veterans organizations, such as the Grand Army of the Republic.<ref>Mears, The Medal of Honor, 43</ref><ref name=\"CMOHS\">[http://www.cmohs.org/medal-types.php Types of Medals of Honor] From the website of the Congressional Medal of Honor Society. Retrieved on July 1, 2012.</ref> To prevent the making of copies of the medal, Brigadier General [[George Lewis Gillespie, Jr.|George Gillespie, Jr.]], a Medal of Honor recipient from the Civil War, applied for and obtained a [[patent]] for the new design.<ref name=\"CMOHS\"/><ref name=\"Design\">{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/patents?id=LP5oAAAAEBAJ&pg=PA1&dq=D37236&source=gbs_selected_pages&cad=1#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Patent number: D37236 |date=1904-11-22 |accessdate=May 16, 2012}}</ref> General Gillespie received the patent on November 22, 1904,<ref name=\"Design\"/> and he transferred it the following month to the Secretary of War at the time, [[William Howard Taft]].<ref name=\"CMOHS\"/>\n* 1923: Congress passed a statute (the year before the 20-year term of the patent would expire)\u2014which would later be codified at 18 U.S.C. \u00a7704\u2014prohibiting the unauthorized wearing, manufacturing, or sale of military medals or decorations.<ref>See [https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/704 Notes to 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 704], citing 42 Stat. 1286. Retrieved on June 30, 2012.</ref> In 1994, Congress amended the statute to permit an enhanced penalty if the offense involved the Medal of Honor.<ref>[http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/BILLS-103hr3355enr/pdf/BILLS-103hr3355enr.pdf Pub.L. 103-322, The Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act of 1994, \u00a7 320109] (page 318 of the PDF version). Retrieved on June 30, 2012.</ref>\n* 2006: The [[Stolen Valor Act of 2005]] was enacted.<ref>[http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/PLAW-109publ437/pdf/PLAW-109publ437.pdf Pub.L. 109-437, The Stolen Valor Act of 2005]. Retrieved on June 30, 2012.</ref> The law amended 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 704 to make it a federal criminal offense for a person to deliberately state falsely that he or she had been awarded a military decoration, service medal, or badge.<ref>''Id..''</ref><ref name=\"s1998track\">{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=s109-1998 |title=S. 1998: Stolen Valor Act of 2005 |website=109th U.S. Congress (2005\u20132006) |publisher=GovTrak.us |accessdate=March 8, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"usc18-704\">{{usc|18|704}}</ref> The law also permitted an enhanced penalty for someone who falsely claimed to have been awarded the Medal of Honor.<ref name=\"usc18-704\"/>\n* June 28, 2012: In the case of ''[[United States v. Alvarez]]'', the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] held that the Stolen Valor Act of 2005's criminalization of the making of false claims of having been awarded a military medal, decoration, or badge was an unconstitutional violation of the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]]'s guarantee of [[free speech]].<ref>[https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/11pdf/11-210d4e9.pdf United States v. Alvarez (slip opinion)], 567 U.S. ___ (2012). Retrieved on June 30, 2012.</ref> The case involved an elected official in [[California]], Xavier Alvarez, who had falsely stated at a public meeting that he had been awarded the Medal of Honor, even though he had never served in any branch of the armed forces. The Supreme Court's decision did not specifically address the constitutionality of the older portion of the statute which prohibits the unauthorized wearing, manufacturing, or sale of military medals or decorations. Under the law, the unauthorized wearing, manufacturing, or sale of the Medal of Honor is punishable by a fine of up to $100,000 and imprisonment of up to one year.<ref>[https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/704 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 704].  ''See also'' [https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/3571 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 3571(b)(5)] (specifying the permissible fine for a federal Class A misdemeanor not resulting in death), and [https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/3559 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 3559(a)(6)] (defining a federal Class A misdemeanor). Retrieved on June 30, 2012.</ref>\n* June 3, 2013: President [[Barack Obama]] signed into law a revised version of the Stolen Valor Act, making it a federal offense for someone to represent themselves as awardees of medals for valor in order to receive benefits or other privileges (such as grants, educational benefits, housing, etc.) that are set aside for veterans and other service members.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.military.com/daily-news/2013/06/03/obama-signs-new-stolen-valor-act.html |title=Obama Signs New Stolen Valor Act |first=Bryant |last=Jordan |date=3 June 2013 |publisher=Military.com |accessdate=28 June 2014}}</ref> As of 2017, there were only two reported arrests and prosecutions under the law, leading at least 22 states to enact their own legislation to criminalize stolen valor amid claims that the federal law was virtually unenforced.<ref>Mary E. Johnston, Combating Thieves of Valor: The Stolen Valor Act of 2013 Is Constitutional Yet Unenforced, 25 Wm. & Mary Bill Rts. J. 1355 (2017), 1358\u20131359</ref>\n\n==Duplicate medals==\nMedal of Honor recipients may apply in writing to the headquarters of the service branch of the medal awarded for a replacement or display Medal of Honor, ribbon, and appurtenance (Medal of Honor flag) without charge. Primary next of kin may also do the same and have any questions answered in regard to the Medal of Honor that was awarded.<ref>DoD Manual 1348.33, Nov. 10, 2010, Vol. 1, P. 29, 6., a., (1), (2) & P. 35, i.</ref>\n\n==Recipients==\n{{Main|List of Medal of Honor recipients}}\n\n* The first Medals of Honor were awarded and presented to six U.S. Army soldiers (\"[[Andrews Raiders]]\") on March 25, 1863, by [[Secretary of War]] [[Edwin Stanton]], in his office of the War Department. Private [[Jacob Parrott]], a U.S. Army volunteer from Ohio, became the first actual Medal of Honor recipient, awarded for his volunteering for and participation in a raid on a [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] train in [[Big Shanty]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] on April 12, 1862, during the [[American Civil War]]. After the medal presentations, the six decorated soldiers met with President Lincoln in the [[White House]].<ref name=\"MWxviii\"/><ref>''Stealing the General: Great Locomotive Chase and The First Medal of Honor'', {{ISBN|1-59416-033-3}}, 2006, by Russell S. Bonds</ref>\n* The first U.S. Navy sailors were awarded the Medal of Honor on April 3, 1863. 41 sailors received the award, with 17 awards for action during the [[Battle of Forts Jackson and St. Philip]]).<ref>Tim Comerford, A Matter of Honor \u2014 History of the Medal of Honor'', https://www.doncio.navy.mil/CHIPS/ArticleDetails.aspx?ID=7419</ref>\n* The first marines awarded the Medal of Honor were [[John F. Mackie]] and [[Pinkerton R. Vaughn]] on July 10, 1863;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcrc.marines.mil/1stmcd/Unit-Home/Cpl-John-F-Mackie/ |title=Cpl Mackie's Actions (''G.O. 17: July 10, 1863. 2 Marines awarded the MOH'') |publisher=U.S. Marine Corps, Marine Corps Recruiting Command, 1st Marine Corps District |accessdate=April 10, 2019}}</ref> Mackie for {{USS|Galena|1862|6}} on May 15, 1862 and Vaughn for {{USS|Mississippi|1841|6}} on March 14, 1863.\n* The first, and so far only, coast guardsman to be awarded the Medal of Honor was Signalman First Class [[Douglas Albert Munro|Douglas Munro]]. He was posthumously awarded it on May 27, 1943, for evacuating 500 marines under fire on September 27, 1942, during the [[Naval Battle of Guadalcanal|Battle of Guadalcanal]].<ref name=CD19>{{harvnb|Collier|Del Calzo|2006|p=19}}</ref> \n* The only woman awarded the Medal of Honor is [[Mary Edwards Walker]], who was a civilian Army surgeon during the American Civil War. She received the award in 1865 after the Judge Advocate General of the Army determined that she could not be given a retroactive commission, and so President Andrew Johnson directed that \"the usual medal of honor for meritorious services be given her.\"<ref name=\"walker\">{{harvnb|Mikaelian|Wallace|2003|p=8}}</ref><ref name=clinic>{{Cite web |accessdate=March 29, 2015 |url=http://www.whitman-walker.org/our-mission-values/our-history/our-namesakes/ |title=About Whitman-Walker Clinic |website=Our History/Our Namesakes |publisher=Whitman-Walker Clinic |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701192148/http://www.whitman-walker.org/our-mission-values/our-history/our-namesakes/ |archivedate=July 1, 2015 }}</ref>\n* The first black Medal of Honor recipients were sixteen Army soldiers and sixteen Navy sailors that fought during the Civil War. The first award was announced on April 6, 1865, to twelve black soldiers from the five regiments of [[United States Colored Troops|U.S. Colored Troops]] who fought at [[Battle of Chaffin's Farm|New Market Heights]] outside of Richmond on September 29, 1864.<ref name=\"Schubert\"/>\n\nThe 1917 Medal of Honor Board deleted 911 awards, but only 910 names from the Army's Medal of Honor list,<ref>Mears, The Medal of Honor, 53, 55</ref> including awards to Dr. Mary Edwards Walker, [[Buffalo Bill|William F. \"Buffalo Bill\" Cody]] and the first of two awards issued February 10, 1887, to George W. Midil, who retained his award issued October 25, 1893. None of the 910 \"deleted\" recipients were ordered to return their medals, although on the question of whether the recipients could continue to wear their medals, the Judge Advocate General advised the Medal of Honor Board the Army was not obligated to police the matter. Walker continued to wear her medal until her death. Although some sources claim that President [[Jimmy Carter]] formally restored her medal posthumously in 1977,<ref name=clinic /> this action was actually taken unilaterally by the Army's Board for Correction of Military Records.<ref>Mears, Medal of Honor, 171</ref> The Army Board for Correction of Military Records also restored the Medals of Honor of Buffalo Bill and four other civilian scouts in 1989.<ref>Mears, Medal of Honor, 175</ref>\n\n* 61 [[Canada|Canadians]] who served in the United States Armed Forces, mostly during the American Civil War. Since 1900, four Canadians have received the medal.<ref name=\"cbc\">{{cite news|date=July 1, 2005 |url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2005/07/01/canadians-usmedal050701.html |title=Canada honours winners of top U.S. medal |publisher=CBC News|accessdate=July 20, 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070529190113/http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2005/07/01/canadians-usmedal050701.html |archivedate=May 29, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> The only Canadian-born, naturalized U.S. citizen to receive the medal for heroism during the Vietnam War was [[Peter C. Lemon]].<ref name=\"vwam\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2005/07/01/canadians-usmedal050701.html |title=Thousands of Canadians, including a Medal of Honor winner, served with the U.S. military in Vietnam |publisher=Veterans With a Mission |accessdate=July 20, 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070529190113/http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2005/07/01/canadians-usmedal050701.html |archivedate=May 29, 2007|url-status=dead | date=July 1, 2005}}</ref>\n\nWhile the governing statute for the Army's Medal of Honor ({{UnitedStatesCode|10|6241}}), beginning in 1918, explicitly stated that a recipient must be \"an officer or enlisted man of the Army\", \"distinguish himself conspicuously by gallantry and intrepidity at the risk of his life above and beyond the call of duty\", and perform an act of valor \"in action involving actual conflict with an enemy\",<ref name=\"Act of July 9, 1918, 40 Stat. 870\"/> exceptions have been made:\n\n* [[Charles Lindbergh]], 1927, civilian pilot, and [[U.S. Army Air Corps]] reserve officer.<ref>\"An Act Authorizing the President of the United States to present in the name of Congress a medal of honor to Colonel Charles A. Lindbergh\", December 14, 1927, HR 3190, Public Law 1, 45 Stat. 1</ref> Lindbergh's medal was authorized by a special act of Congress.<ref name=\"Act of July 9, 1918, 40 Stat. 870\"/><ref>Mears, Medal of Honor, 91</ref>\n* Major General (Retired) [[Adolphus Greely]] was awarded the medal in 1935, on his 91st birthday, \"for his life of splendid public service\". The result of a special act of Congress similar to Lindbergh's, Greely's medal citation did not reference any acts of valor.<ref>William Putnam, ''Arctic Superstars: The Scientific Exploration and Study of High Mountain Elevations and of the Regions Lying Within or about the Arctic and Antarctic Circles '' (Boulder, CO: American Alpine Club, 2001), 171.</ref> \n* Foreign unknown recipients include the [[Tomb of the Unknown Soldier (Belgium)|Belgian Unknown Soldier]], the [[The Unknown Warrior|British Unknown Warrior]], the [[Tomb of the Unknown Soldier (France)|French Unknown Soldier]], the [[Tomb of the Unknown Soldier (Italy)|Italian Unknown Soldier]], and the [[Tomb of the Unknown Soldier (Romania)|Romanian Unknown Soldier]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/asaoc.html |title=Medal of Honor Recipients \u2013 Authorized by Special Acts of Congress |publisher=History.army.mil |date= |accessdate=May 26, 2012}}</ref>\n* U.S. unknown recipients include the Unknowns of World War I,<ref>War Department General orders, No. 59, 13 December 1921, Sec. I</ref> World War II,<ref>Approved March 9, 1948, Public Law 438, Eightieth Congress</ref> Korea,<ref>Approved August 31, 1957, Public Law 85-251 Eighty-fifth Congress</ref> and Vietnam.<ref>Approved May 25, 1984, Public Law 98-301, Ninety-eighth Congress</ref> The Vietnam Unknown was later identified as Air Force First Lieutenant [[Michael J. Blassie]] through the use of DNA identification. Blassie's family asked for his Medal of Honor, but the Department of Defense denied the request in 1998. According to Undersecretary of Defense Rudy de Leon, the medal was awarded symbolically to all Vietnam unknowns, not to Blassie specifically.<ref>{{cite newspaper |title=Medal of Honor Won't Join Once-unknown Pilot |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=August 23, 1998}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=15%|Conflict!!width=15%|Date!!width=15%|Medal count (3,525)!! class=\"unsortable\" |List article\n|-\n|[[American Civil War|Civil War]]\n|1861\u20131865\n|1,523\n|[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients|American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients]]\n|-\n|[[Indian Wars]]\n| 1865\u20131891\n|426\n|[[List of Medal of Honor recipients for the Indian Wars|Medal of Honor recipients for the Indian Wars]]\n|-\n|[[Sinmiyangyo|Korean Expedition]]\n| 1871\n|15\n|[[List of Medal of Honor recipients#Korean Expedition|Medal of Honor recipients in Korea]]\n|-\n|[[Spanish\u2013American War]]\n| 1898\n|110\n|[[List of Medal of Honor recipients for the Spanish\u2013American War|Medal of Honor recipients for the Spanish\u2013American War]]\n|-\n|[[Second Samoan Civil War]]\n| 1899\n|4\n|[[List of Medal of Honor recipients#Samoan Civil War|Medal of Honor recipients for the Samoan Civil War]]\n|-\n|[[Philippine\u2013American War]]\n| 1899\u20131902\n|86\n|[[List of Philippine\u2013American War Medal of Honor recipients|Philippine\u2013American War Medal of Honor recipients]]\n|-\n|[[Boxer Rebellion]]\n| 1899\u20131901\n|59\n|[[List of Medal of Honor recipients for the Boxer Rebellion|Medal of Honor recipients for the Boxer Rebellion]]\n|-\n|[[United States occupation of Veracruz|Occupation of Veracruz]]\n| 1914\n|56\n|[[List of Medal of Honor recipients (Veracruz)|Medal of Honor recipients for Veracruz]]\n|-\n|[[United States occupation of Haiti]