]\n|-\n|[[Tomb of the Unknown Soldier|Unknown soldiers]]\n|\n|9\n|[[List of Medal of Honor recipients#Foreign|Unknown Medal of Honor recipients]]\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto;\"\n|+'''Awards by military branch'''\n|-<!--Header-->\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#EFEFEF; color:black; width:100px;\"| Army\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#EFEFEF; color:black; width:100px;\"| Navy\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#EFEFEF; color:black; width:100px;\"| Marine Corps\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#EFEFEF; color:black; width:100px;\"| Air Force\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#EFEFEF; color:black; width:100px;\"| Coast Guard\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#EFEFEF; color:black; width:100px;\"| Total\n|-<!--Row 1-->\n|align=center| 2,457\n|align=center|  748\n|align=center|  300\n|align=center|   19\n|align=center|    1\n|align=center| 3,525\n|}{{efn|The total 3,524 includes the award presented by President Trump on June 25, 2019. The U.S. Army total includes five First World War Army medals awarded to U.S. marines who were later awarded the Naval Medal of Honor for the same deed. However, the award to marine [[Fred W. Stockman]], who was only awarded the Army Medal of Honor is counted in the USMC total.}} <sup>Citation required for service totals.</sup>\n\n===Double recipients===\nNineteen servicemembers have been awarded the Medal of Honor twice.<ref>{{harvnb|Tucker|2012|p=2,359}}</ref> The first double Medal of Honor recipient was [[Thomas Custer]] (brother of [[George Armstrong Custer]]) for two separate actions that took place several days apart during the American Civil War.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.history.army.mil/moh/civilwar_af.html#CUSTER |title = Medal of Honor Recipients: Thomas W. Custer |publisher = United States Army Center of Military History |accessdate = September 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFive \"double recipients\" were awarded both the Army's and Navy's Medal of Honor for the same action, with all five of these occurrences taking place during World War I.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/mohstats.html |title=Medal of Honor Statistics |publisher=History.army.mil |date= |accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref> No modern recipients have more than one medal because of laws passed for the Army in 1918, and for the Navy in 1919, which stipulated that \"no more than one medal of honor . . . shall be issued to any one person,\" although subsequent awards were authorized by issuance of bars or other devices in lieu of the medal itself.<ref>Mears, The Medal of Honor, 219, 221</ref> The statutory bar was finally repealed in the FY2014 defense bill, at the request of the Office of the Secretary of Defense, meaning that recipients can now be issued more than one medal.<ref>Mears, The Medal of Honor, 130</ref>\n\nTo date, the maximum number of Medals of Honor earned by any service member has been two.<ref name=navyfaq/> The last living individual to be awarded two Medals of Honor was [[John J. Kelly]] 3 Oct 1918; the last individual to receive two Medals of Honor for two different actions was [[Smedley Butler]], in 1914 and 1915.\n\n:<small> \u00a7 Rank refers to rank held at time of Medal of Honor action.</small>\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable nowraplinks\"\n|-\n! Name !! Service !! Rank<sup>\u00a7</sup> !! War(s) !! Notes\n|-\n|<span style=\"display:none;\">Baldwin</span>[[Frank Baldwin]]||[[US Army|Army]]||First Lieutenant, Captain||[[American Civil War]], [[Indian Wars]]||\n|-\n|<span style=\"display:none;\">Butler</span>[[Smedley Butler]]||[[US Marine Corps|Marine Corps]]||Major General||[[United States occupation of Veracruz|Veracruz]], [[United States occupation of Haiti|Haiti]]||\n|-\n|<span style=\"display:none;\">Cooper</span>[[John Laver Mather Cooper|John Cooper]]||[[US Navy|Navy]]||[[Coxswain]]||American Civil War||\n|-\n|<span style=\"display:none;\">Cukela</span>[[Louis Cukela]]||Marine Corps||Sergeant||[[World War I]]||Awarded both Navy and Army versions for same action.\n|-\n|<span style=\"display:none;\">Custer</span>[[Thomas Custer]]||Army||Second Lieutenant||American Civil War||[[Battle of Namozine Church]] on 3 April and [[Battle of Sayler's Creek]] on 6 April 1865.\n|-\n|<span style=\"display:none;\">Daly</span>[[Daniel Daly]]||Marine Corps||Private, Gunnery Sergeant||[[Boxer Rebellion]], Haiti||<ref>[http://www.stephenwscott.com/ \"Scott, Stephen W.\"]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, (2009) Sergeant Major Dan Daly; The Most Outstanding Marine of all Time. Publishamerica Publishers. {{ISBN|1-60836-465-8}}.</ref>\n|-\n|<span style=\"display:none;\">Hogan</span>[[Henry Hogan]]||Army||First Sergeant||Indian Wars||\n|-\n|<span style=\"display:none;\">Janson</span>[[Ernest A. Janson]]||Marine Corps||Gunnery Sergeant||World War I||Both awarded for same action. Received the Army MOH under the name Charles F. Hoffman.\n|-\n|<span style=\"display:none;\">Kelly</span>[[John J. Kelly]]||Marine Corps||Private||World War I||Both awarded for same action.\n|-\n|<span style=\"display:none;\">King</span>[[John King (sailor)|John King]]||Navy||Water tender||Peacetime||1901 and 1909\n|-\n|<span style=\"display:none;\">Kocak</span>[[Matej Kocak]]||Marine Corps||Sergeant||World War I||Both awarded for same action.\n|-\n|<span style=\"display:none;\">Lafferty</span>[[John Lafferty]]||Navy||{{nowrap|Fireman, First Class Fireman}}||American Civil War, peacetime||\n|-\n|<span style=\"display:none;\">McCloy</span>[[John C. McCloy]]||Navy||Coxswain, Chief Boatswain||Boxer Rebellion, Veracruz||\n|-\n|<span style=\"display:none;\">Mullen</span>[[Patrick Mullen (Medal of Honor)|Patrick Mullen]]||Navy||Boatswain's Mate||American Civil War||\n|-\n|<span style=\"display:none;\">Pruitt</span>[[John H. Pruitt]]||Marine Corps||Corporal||World War I||Both awarded for same action.\n|-\n|<span style=\"display:none;\">Sweeney</span>[[Robert Augustus Sweeney|Robert Sweeney]]||Navy||Ordinary Seaman||Peacetime||1881 and 1883\n|-\n|<span style=\"display:none;\">Weisbogel</span>[[Albert Weisbogel]]||Navy||Captain of the Mizzen Top ||Peacetime||1874 and 1876\n|-\n|<span style=\"display:none;\">Williams</span>[[Ludwig Andreas Olsen|Louis Williams]]||Navy||Captain of the Hold||Peacetime||1883 and 1884. Also known as [[Ludwig Andreas Olsen]].\n|-\n|<span style=\"display:none;\">Wilson</span>[[William Wilson (soldier)|William Wilson]]||Army||Sergeant||Indian Wars||\n|}\n\n===Related recipients===\n[[Arthur MacArthur, Jr.]] and [[Douglas MacArthur]] are the first father and son to be awarded the Medal of Honor. The only other such pairing is [[Theodore Roosevelt]] (awarded in 2001) and [[Theodore Roosevelt, Jr.]]\n\nFive pairs of brothers have received the Medal of Honor:\n* [[John C. Black|John]] and [[William P. Black|William Black]], in the [[American Civil War]]. The Blacks are the first brothers to be so honored.\n* [[Charles E. Capehart|Charles]] and [[Henry Capehart]], in the American Civil War, the latter for saving a drowning man while under fire.\n* [[Antoine August Michel Gaujot|Antoine]] and [[Julien Edmund Victor Gaujot|Julien Gaujot]]. The Gaujots also have the unique distinction of receiving their medals for actions in separate conflicts, Antoine in the [[Philippine\u2013American War]] and Julien when he crossed the Mexican border to rescue Mexicans and Americans in a [[Mexican Revolution]] skirmish.\n* [[Harry Herbert Miller|Harry]] and [[Willard Miller]], during the same naval action in the [[Spanish\u2013American War]].\n* [[Allen and James Thompson]], in the same American Civil War action.\nAnother notable pair of related recipients are Admiral [[Frank Friday Fletcher]] (rear admiral at the time of award) and his nephew, Admiral [[Frank Jack Fletcher]] (lieutenant at the time of award), both awarded for actions during the [[United States occupation of Veracruz]].\n\n===Late awards===\nSince 1979, 86 late Medal of Honor awards have been presented for actions from the Civil War to the Vietnam War. In addition, five recipients whose names were not included on the Army's Medal of Honor Roll in 1917 had their awards restored.<ref>Congressional Research Service, Medal of Honor Recipients: 1979\u20132014, Anne Leland, Information Research Specialist, December 2, 2014, https://www.fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/RL30011.pdf. The report lists the late awards until the end of 2014. six additional late awards have been presented at the White House, three by President Obama in 2015 and 2016 and three by President Trump in 2017 and 2018.</ref> \nA 1993 study commissioned by the U.S. Army investigated \"racial disparity\" in the awarding of medals.<ref name=\"African\">{{cite web|url = http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/mohb.html |title = WWII African American MOH recipients |publisher= [[United States Army Center of Military History]] |accessdate = July 20, 2006}}</ref> At the time, no Medals of Honor had been awarded to U.S. soldiers of [[African descent]] who served in World War II. After an exhaustive review, the study recommended that ten [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]] recipients be awarded the Medal of Honor. On January 13, 1997, President [[Bill Clinton]] presented the Medal of Honor to seven of these World War II veterans, six of them posthumously and one to former Second Lieutenant [[Vernon Baker]].<ref name=CD25/>\n\nIn 1998, a similar study of [[Asian American]]s resulted in President [[Bill Clinton]] presenting 22 Medals of Honor in 2000.<ref name=\"AsianDoD\">{{cite web |url=http://archive.defense.gov/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=45241 |title=22 Asian Americans Inducted into Hall of Heroes |author=Rudi Williams |date=28 June 2000 |website=American Forces Press Service |publisher=United States Department of Defense |accessdate=9 March 2013}}</ref> Twenty of these medals went to U.S. soldiers of [[Japanese people|Japanese]] descent of the [[442nd Regimental Combat Team]] (442nd RCT) who served in the [[European Theater of Operations]] during World War II.<ref name=\"AsianDoD\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Today, an old wrong is righted as 22 Asian-American heroes are awarded the nation's highest honor for bravery in battle |author=Gregg K. Kakesako |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2000/06/21/special/ |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |date=21 June 2000 |accessdate=9 March 2013}}</ref> One of these Medal of Honor recipients was Senator [[Daniel Inouye]], a former U.S. Army officer in the 442nd RCT.<ref name=CD25>{{harvnb|Collier|Del Calzo|2006|p=25}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, President [[George W. Bush]] presented the Medal of Honor to [[Tibor Rubin]], a [[Hungary|Hungarian]]-born [[American Jews|American Jew]] who was a [[Holocaust survivor]] of World War II and enlisted U.S. infantryman and [[prisoner of war]] in the [[Korean War]], whom many believed to have been overlooked because of his [[religion]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Medal of Honor recipient just did duty |author=Nguyen Huy Vu |url=http://www.ocregister.com/news/medal-207819-honor-rubin.html |newspaper=Orange County Register |date=18 October 2005 |accessdate=9 March 2013}}<br />{{cite news |title=Pentagon Reviews Jewish Veteran Files |author=Tom Tugend |url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/community_briefs/article/pentagon_reviews_jewish_veteran_files_20020517 |newspaper=Jewish Journal |date=16 May 2002 |accessdate=28 September 2015 }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.army.mil/medalofhonor/rubin/profile/index.html |title=Corporal Tibor Rubin, Korean War Veteran |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=1 February 2013 |website=Medal of Honor Corporal Tibor Rubin |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=9 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn April 11, 2013, President Obama presented the Medal of Honor posthumously to [[Chaplain Corps (United States Army)|Army chaplain]] Captain [[Emil Kapaun]] for his actions as a [[Korean War#Prisoners of war|prisoner of war]] during the Korean War.<ref>{{cite AV media |people=Barack Obama |year=2013 |title=Army Chaplain Gets Posthumous Medal of Honor |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PV-Y2N_z3FE |accessdate=16 April 2013 |publisher=Associated Press}}<br />{{cite news |title=Medal of Honor for US Army chaplain Father Kapaun  |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-22111385 |publisher=BBC News |date=11 April 2013 |accessdate=16 April 2013}}<br />{{cite news |title=Obama awards Kapaun Medal of Honor |author=Krissah Thompson |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2013/04/11/obama-awards-kapaun-medal-of-honor/ |newspaper=Washington Post |date=11 April 2013 |accessdate=16 April 2013}}</ref> This follows other awards to Army Sergeant [[Leslie H. Sabo, Jr.]] for conspicuous gallantry in action on May 10, 1970, near [[Tonl\u00e9 San|Se San]], [[Cambodia]], during the Vietnam War<ref name=cbsnews5-16-12>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-201_162-57435607/gi-killed-in-vietnam-war-receives-medal-of-honor/ |title=GI killed in Vietnam War receives Medal of Honor |publisher=CBS News |date=May 16, 2012 |accessdate=May 16, 2012}}</ref> and to Army Private First Class [[Henry Svehla]] and Army Private First Class [[Anthony T. Kaho\u02bbohanohano]] for their heroic actions during the Korean War.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Marsh |first=Wendell |title=Two Korean War vets receive Medal of Honor posthumously |publisher=Reuters |date=May 2, 2011 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/05/02/us-obama-medals-idUSTRE7416NA20110502 |archiveurl =https://www.webcitation.org/5ySuVarC7?url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/05/02/us-obama-medals-idUSTRE7416NA20110502 |archivedate= May 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of a Congressionally mandated review to ensure brave acts were not overlooked due to prejudice or discrimination, on March 18, 2014, President Obama upgraded [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Crosses]] to Medals of Honor for 24 Hispanic, Jewish, and African American individuals\u2014the \"Valor 24\"\u2014for their actions in World War II, the Korean War and the Vietnam War.<ref name=USarmyCAC201403/> Three were still living at the time of the ceremony.<ref name=USarmyCAC201403>\u2022 {{cite web |title=Valor 24 / Medal of Honor / World War II Korean War Vietnam War |url=http://usacac.army.mil/CAC2/MilitaryReview/Archives/English/MilitaryReview_20140630_art019.pdf |publisher=U.S. Army Combined Arms Center |accessdate=June 3, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Q3W0ebRk?url=http://usacac.army.mil/CAC2/MilitaryReview/Archives/English/MilitaryReview_20140630_art019.pdf |archivedate=June 3, 2014 |date=March 18, 2014}} \u2022 List with basic details is at U.S. Army's [http://www.army.mil/medalofhonor/valor24/recipients/ List of Recipients].</ref>\n\n==27th Maine and other revoked awardings==\n[[File:Medal of Honor monument, Austin, TX IMG 2206.JPG|right|thumb|A Medal of Honor monument at the [[Texas State Cemetery]] in [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], [[Texas]]]]\n\nDuring the Civil War, [[United States Secretary of War|Secretary of War]] [[Edwin M. Stanton]] promised a Medal of Honor to every man in the [[27th Maine Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] who extended his enlistment beyond the agreed-upon date. The Battle of Gettysburg was imminent, and 311 men of the regiment volunteered to serve until the battle was resolved. The remaining men returned to Maine, but with the Union victory at Gettysburg the 311 volunteers soon followed. The volunteers arrived back in Maine in time to be discharged with the men who had returned earlier. Since there seemed to be no official list of the 311 volunteers, the [[United States Department of War|War Department]] exacerbated the situation by forwarding 864 medals to the commanding officer of the regiment. The commanding officer only issued the medals to the volunteers who stayed behind and retained the others on the grounds that, if he returned the remainder to the War Department, the War Department would try to reissue the medals.<ref name=\"MWxix\">{{harvnb|Mikaelian|Wallace|2003|p=xix}}</ref>\n\nIn 1916, a board of five Army generals on the retired list convened under act of law to review every Army Medal of Honor awarded. The board was to report on any Medals of Honor awarded or issued \"for any cause other than distinguished conduct by an officer or enlisted man in action involving actual conflict with an enemy.\"<ref name=\"Mears, The Medal of Honor, 53\"/> The commission, led by [[Nelson A. Miles]], identified 911 awards for causes other than distinguished conduct. This included the 864 medals awarded to members of the 27th Maine regiment; 29 servicemen who served as [[Abraham Lincoln]]'s funeral guard; six civilians, including [[Mary Edwards Walker]] and [[Buffalo Bill|Buffalo Bill Cody]]; and 12 others.<ref name=\"MWxxv\">{{harvnb|Mikaelian|Wallace|2003|p=xxv}}</ref><ref name=CD15>{{harvnb|Collier|Del Calzo|2006|p=15}}</ref> Walker's medal was restored by the Army Board for Correction of Military Records in 1977, an action that is often attributed to President Jimmy Carter in error.<ref>Mears, The Medal of Honor, 168, 171</ref> Cody and four other civilian scouts who rendered distinguished service in action, and who were therefore considered by the board to have fully earned their medals, also had their medals restored by the Army Board for Correction of Military Records in 1989.<ref name=CD16>{{harvnb|Collier|Del Calzo|2006|p=16}}</ref> The report issued by the Medal of Honor review board in 1917 was reviewed by the [[Judge Advocate General's Corps|Judge Advocate General]], who also advised that the War Department should not seek the return of the revoked medals from the recipients identified by the board. In the case of recipients who continued to wear the medal, the War Department was advised to take no action to enforce the statute.<ref>66th Congress 1st Session, Document 58, General Staff and Medals of Honor, ordered to be printed 23 July 1919.</ref>\n\n==Similarly-named U.S. decorations==\nThe following decorations, in one degree or another, bear similar names to the Medal of Honor, but are entirely separate awards with different criteria for issuance:\n\n* [[Cardenas Medal of Honor]]: decoration of the [[United States Revenue Cutter Service]], which was later merged into the [[United States Coast Guard]]\n* [[Chaplain's Medal for Heroism]]: awarded posthumously for a single action to [[Four Chaplains|four recipients]]\n* [[Congressional Gold Medal]]: the highest civilian honor bestowed by the United States (along with the Presidential Medal of Freedom)\n* [[Congressional Space Medal of Honor]]: the highest honor for NASA astronauts\n* [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]]: the highest civilian honor bestowed by the United States (along with the Congressional Gold Medal)\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Medal of Honor recipients]]\n* [[Distinguished Intelligence Cross]]\n* [[Merchant Marine Distinguished Service Medal]] \n* [[Kentucky Medal of Honor Memorial]]\n* [[Medal of Honor Memorial (Indianapolis)]]\n* [[Military awards and decorations]]\n* [[Pueblo, Colorado#Home of Heroes|Home of the Heroes]], a recognition of [[Pueblo, Colorado]] for being the hometown of four Medal of Honor recipients (claimed to be more recipients per capita than any other city in the United States)\n* [[Texas Medal of Honor Memorial]]\n* [[African-American Medal of Honor Recipients Memorial]]\n\n==References==\n===Footnotes===\n{{Notelist}}\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Works cited===\n* {{ACMH|article = |url = |author = |accessdate =}}{{nonspecific|date=March 2018}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Broadwater |first=Robert P. |title=Civil War Medal of Honor Recipients: A Complete Illustrated Record |location=Jefferson, NC |publisher=McFarland & Co. |year=2007 |isbn=978-0-7864-3223-3 |oclc=144767966}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Collier |first=Peter |last2=Del Calzo |first2=Nick |title=Medal of Honor: Portraits of Valor Beyond the Call of Duty |year=2006 |edition=2nd |location=New York |publisher=[[Workman Publishing Company]] |isbn=978-1-57965-314-9 |oclc=852666368 |ref=harv |url=https://archive.org/details/medalofhonorport00coll }}\n* {{Cite book |last=Collier |first=Peter |last2=Del Calzo |first2=Nick |title=Medal of Honor: Portraits of Valor Beyond the Call of Duty |year=2011 |edition=3rd |location=New York |publisher=Artisan |isbn=978-1-57965-462-7 |oclc=712124011}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Curtis |first=Arthur S. |title=37 Greatest Navy Heroes: Including the Story of Marvin Shields, First Seabee Medal of Honor Hero (Vietnam) |location=Washington, D.C. |year=1969 |oclc=10660663}}\n* {{Cite book |last=DeKever |first=Andrew J. |title=Here Rests in Honored Glory: Life Stories of Our Country's Medal of Honor Recipients |location=Bennigton, Vermont |publisher=Merriam Press |year=2008 |isbn=978-1-4357-1749-7 |oclc=233835859}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Foster |first=Frank C. |title=A Complete Guide to All United States Military Medals, 1939 to Present |location=Fountain Inn, S.C. |publisher=MOA Press |year=2002 |isbn=978-1-884452-18-5 |oclc=54755134}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Hanna |first=Charles W. |title=African American Recipients of the Medal of Honor: A Biographical Dictionary, Civil War Through Vietnam War |location=Jefferson, N.C. |publisher=Mcfarland |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-7864-4911-8 |oclc=476156919}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Johnson |first=John L. |title=Every Night & Every Morn: Portraits of Asian, Hispanic, Jewish, African-American, and Native-American Recipients of the Congressional Medal of Honor |location=Winston-Salem, NC |publisher=Tristan Press |year=2007 |isbn=978-0-9799572-0-8 |oclc=180773640}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Mears |first=Dwight S. |title=The Medal of Honor: The Evolution of America's Highest Military Decoration |location=Lawrence, KS |publisher=University Press of Kansas |year=2018 |isbn=9780700626656 |oclc=1032014828}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Mikaelian |firs